Subject: [PATCH] ppu/include: PSL1GHT owns <sys/stat.h>, drops newlib's time macros

Newlib 4.4's <sys/stat.h> unconditionally #defines the legacy
`st_atime` / `st_mtime` / `st_ctime` tokens as backward-compat
aliases for the POSIX-2008 `st_atim.tv_sec` etc. timespec-member
forms.  Those #defines bleed into every subsequent translation-unit
token — including unrelated struct declarations (PSL1GHT's
sysFSStat, Sony's CellFsStat, or any user-defined struct whose
author happened to pick the same member name).  The original
`patches/psl1ght/0003` dodged the collision per-site with a
`#pragma push_macro / #undef / pop_macro` dance around the sysFSStat
typedef.  That's ugly and brittle (every new struct elsewhere would
need the same guard).

Ship a PSL1GHT-owned <sys/stat.h> that takes priority over newlib's
(because `$PSL1GHT/ppu/include` is passed via `-I`, which GCC scans
before the -isystem toolchain include path).  It pulls newlib's
declarations via `#include_next <sys/stat.h>` and then #undefines the
three legacy macros.  Result: struct stat stays in its
POSIX-2008-shaped timespec form, other structs can use the same
member names as literal fields, and no per-site pragma is needed.

Callers that were relying on the macro to access `sb.st_atime` as a
shortcut for `sb.st_atim.tv_sec` must migrate to the full timespec
form.  Matches Sony's SDK convention (Sony never defined those
macros either) and POSIX.1-2017 guidance.  Inside PSL1GHT itself only
librt/fstat.c and lv2/sysfs.h ever mentioned the tokens; both sites
accept the new rule.

Retires the pragma dance in patches/psl1ght/0003 — that patch is
shrunk in the same commit.

diff --git a/ppu/include/sys/stat.h b/ppu/include/sys/stat.h
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..88173ff
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ppu/include/sys/stat.h
@@ -0,0 +1,41 @@
+/*! \file sys/stat.h
+ \brief PSL1GHT override of newlib's <sys/stat.h>.
+
+  PSL1GHT-owned shadow.  Pulls newlib's declarations via #include_next,
+  then undefines the POSIX-2008-compat macros that otherwise rewrite
+  `st_atime` / `st_mtime` / `st_ctime` into `st_atim.tv_sec` etc.
+  wherever those tokens appear in subsequent source — including in
+  unrelated structs (PSL1GHT's sysFSStat, Sony's CellFsStat, any
+  user-defined struct that happens to use the same member name).
+
+  Rationale:
+    - Sony's reference SDK (475.001) never defined these macros.
+    - Newlib 4.4's unconditional #defines made it impossible to
+      declare `st_atime` as a struct member without pragma gymnastics
+      (see the original patches/psl1ght/0003 push_macro/pop_macro dance).
+    - Undefining once, early, is cleaner than pragma-guarding every
+      site.
+
+  Impact on user code:
+    - Nanosecond-precision access via `sb.st_atim.tv_sec` / `.tv_nsec`
+      still works; those are real struct members.
+    - `sb.st_atime` as a shortcut for `sb.st_atim.tv_sec` NO LONGER
+      compiles.  Migrate to the full timespec form.  This matches the
+      Sony SDK convention and POSIX.1-2017 guidance.
+*/
+#ifndef _PSL1GHT_SYS_STAT_H
+#define _PSL1GHT_SYS_STAT_H
+
+#include_next <sys/stat.h>
+
+#ifdef st_atime
+#undef st_atime
+#endif
+#ifdef st_mtime
+#undef st_mtime
+#endif
+#ifdef st_ctime
+#undef st_ctime
+#endif
+
+#endif /* _PSL1GHT_SYS_STAT_H */
